Before diving into the best practices, please note that you may need to adapt the globs depending on your specific project structure.

---
name: nextjs-best-practices.mdc
description: Best practices for Next.js applications and routing
globs: **/*.{ts,tsx}
---

- Use the App Router for better performance and simpler routing
- Implement proper error boundaries with `error.tsx` files
- Use `loading.tsx` for loading states to improve user experience
- Keep route-specific logic in `route.ts` files
- Utilize Next.js built-in optimizations like image optimization and code splitting

---
name: react-best-practices.mdc
description: Best practices for React component development
globs: **/*.{tsx,jsx}
---

- Use functional components with hooks instead of class components
- Keep components small and focused on a single responsibility
- Utilize React.memo for performance optimization of pure components
- Use the Context API for global state management
- Implement proper prop type validation with TypeScript

---
name: typescript-best-practices.mdc
description: TypeScript coding standards and type safety guidelines
globs: **/*.{ts,tsx}
---

- Enable strict mode in tsconfig.json for better type checking
- Use interfaces for object shapes and type aliases for unions and intersections
- Leverage type inference to reduce unnecessary type annotations
- Use readonly arrays and tuples when possible to prevent unintended mutations
- Implement custom type guards for runtime type checking

---
name: shadcn-ui-best-practices.mdc
description: Best practices for using Shadcn UI components
globs: **/*.{tsx,jsx}
---

- Use Shadcn UI components as building blocks for your custom components
- Customize components using the `className` prop and Tailwind CSS utilities
- Override default styles by passing custom class names
- Utilize the `asChild` prop to render components as different HTML elements
- Keep custom components DRY by composing Shadcn UI primitives

---
name: tailwindcss-best-practices.mdc
description: Best practices for using Tailwind CSS
globs: **/*.{tsx,jsx,css}
---

- Use utility classes directly in your JSX for faster development
- Create custom utility classes for frequently used styles
- Utilize the `@apply` directive in CSS files for complex styles
- Keep your `tailwind.config.js` organized and DRY
- Use responsive prefixes for mobile-first design

---
name: react-context-best-practices.mdc
description: Best practices for using React Context API
globs: src/context/**/*.{ts,tsx}
---

- Use context for global state that is needed by many components
- Create separate context for different domains of your application
- Use the `useContext` hook instead of `Context.Consumer` for better readability
- Implement custom hooks to abstract context usage
- Avoid overusing context; prefer props for component-specific data

---
name: react-hooks-best-practices.mdc
description: Best practices for creating custom React hooks
globs: src/hooks/**/*.{ts,tsx}
---

- Name hooks with the `use` prefix to follow React conventions
- Keep hooks focused on a single responsibility
- Use `useCallback` and `useMemo` for performance optimization
- Implement error handling and loading states in data-fetching hooks
- Document hook usage, parameters, and return values

---
name: typescript-types-best-practices.mdc
description: Best practices for defining TypeScript types
globs: src/types/**/*.ts
---

- Use interfaces for object shapes and type aliases for unions and intersections
- Group related types in a single file for better organization
- Use generics for reusable types
- Implement branded types for runtime type safety
- Use utility types like `Partial`, `Readonly`, and `Pick` for type manipulation